  "name": "Morrison COU1 — CPB hemolysis credibility assessment",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under cardiopulmonary bypass (CPB) conditions. COU1 evaluates whether the computational model can identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for a Class II CPB device at Model Risk Level 2. Full 13-factor assessment: 7 factors assessed (all meeting required levels), 6 factors not assessed (acceptable at MRL 2).",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/morrison-cpb-hemolysis-mrl2",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/morrison-cou1-worst-case-hemolysis",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/morrison-cfd-hemolysis-powerlaw",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-fda-pump-experimental-rbc-lysis",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-cfd-shear-stress-history-5pts"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-01-rsquared-fit",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Power-law hemolysis model R-squared fit to experimental calibration data",
      "description": "The CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were regressed against experimental plasma free haemoglobin measurements at the five calibration operating points (2.5 L/min at 2500 RPM, 4 L/min at 3000 RPM, 5 L/min at 3500 RPM, 6 L/min at 3800 RPM, 7 L/min at 4200 RPM). A coefficient of determination R²=0.974 was obtained, indicating that the power-law model constants (C=3.62×10⁻⁷, α=2.416, β=0.785) capture 97.4% of the variance in the calibration dataset. This high R² value is presented as primary evidence that the model is suitable for identifying worst-case hemolysis conditions across the operating envelope.",
      "metricName": "R-squared (coefficient of determination) on calibration dataset",
      "metricValue": "0.974",
      "assessmentNote": "R² computed over the same five operating points used to fit the power-law exponents. No held-out test points or cross-validation were performed. The metric quantifies in-sample curve-fit quality and does not evaluate the model's ability to rank-order or bound hemolysis at untested worst-case conditions, which is the actual question posed by the COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-02-pearson-correlation",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Pearson correlation between CFD NIH and experimental NIH at calibration points",
      "description": "Pearson correlation coefficient r=0.987 (p<0.001) was computed between CFD-predicted NIH and experimentally measured NIH across the five calibration flow-speed combinations. The near-unity correlation is cited as confirmation that the hemolysis model tracks experimental trends faithfully. Because the COU acceptance criterion is RH<1 (relative hemolysis index versus a predicate device), the relevant validation metric should quantify the uncertainty in predicted RH at operating conditions outside the calibration set, particularly at the geometrically extreme tolerance variants. The Pearson correlation reported here does not address prediction uncertainty, extrapolation error, or the probability that the worst-case RH prediction exceeds the acceptance threshold.",
      "metricName": "Pearson correlation coefficient on calibration dataset",
      "metricValue": "0.987",
      "assessmentNote": "Pearson r reflects linear association within the training sample. It is insensitive to systematic bias and provides no information on prediction interval width at deployment conditions. Reporting this metric as validation evidence for a worst-case-identification COU constitutes an inadequate metric choice."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-03-rh-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Relative hemolysis index comparison at nominal operating point",
      "description": "At the single nominal operating condition (5 L/min, 3500 RPM), the computed relative hemolysis index RH=0.83 satisfies the RH<1 acceptance criterion relative to the predicate device. This point-wise comparison is presented as supporting evidence for COU acceptance. However, no sensitivity analysis across the five worst-case tolerance variants was performed using held-out experimental data; the RH value is derived entirely from the same CFD model whose constants were fitted to the calibration data, creating a circularity. The validation dataset used for this comparison is identical to the calibration dataset.",
      "metricName": "Relative hemolysis index (RH) at nominal condition only",
      "metricValue": "0.83",
      "assessmentNote": "Single-point RH check at nominal conditions does not constitute validation of worst-case identification capability across the operating envelope. The COU requires evidence that the model correctly ranks hemolysis severity across geometric variants; this metric does not provide that evidence."
    }
  ],
